3 Section 3. Section 2-15-3112, MCA, is amended to read:
4 "2-15-3112. Livestock loss mitigation program -- definitions. The livestock loss board shall
5 establish and administer a program to reimburse livestock producers for livestock losses caused by wolves,
6 mountain lions, black bears, and grizzly bears, subject to the following provisions:
7 (1) The board shall establish eligibility requirements for reimbursement, which must provide that all
8 Montana livestock producers are eligible for coverage for losses by wolves, mountain lions, black bears, and
9 grizzly bears to cattle, swine, horses, mules, sheep, goats, llamas, and livestock guard dogs on state, federal,
10 tribal, and private land.
11 (2) (a) Except as provided in subsection (2)(b), the board may reimburse confirmed and probable
12 livestock losses at an amount not to exceed the fair market value of the livestock.
13 (b) The board may reimburse confirmed and probable livestock losses by paying a multiplier of the
14 fair market value of the livestock based on a board-determined region.
15 (c) Before the board may issue a reimbursement for losses to a livestock producer eligible for
16 coverage for losses, the department of revenue shall certify that the livestock producer has paid per capita fees
17 as required by 15-24-921. Except for a tribal member or tribal entity participating in an authorized agreement
18 pursuant to 2-15-3113, a livestock producer may not receive a reimbursement for losses until the producer has
19 paid any delinquent per capita fees.
20 (3) Other losses may be reimbursed at rates determined by the board.
21 (4) A claim process must be established to be used when a livestock producer suffers a livestock
22 loss for which wolves, mountain lions, black bears, or grizzly bears may be responsible. The claim process
23 must set out a clear and concise method for documenting and processing claims for reimbursement for
24 livestock losses.
25 (5) Names, addresses, and other personally identifiable information of claimants must remain
26 confidential and may not be released.
27 (6) (a) A process must be established to allow livestock producers to appeal reimbursement
28 decisions. A producer may appeal a staff adjuster's decision by notifying the staff adjuster and the board in
- 3 - Authorized Print Version – HB 356

