1 writing, stating the reasons for the appeal and providing documentation supporting the appeal. If the
2 documentation is incomplete, the board or a producer may consult with the U.S. department of agriculture
3 wildlife services to complete the documentation.
4 (b) The board may not accept any appeal on the question of whether the loss was or was not a
5 confirmed or probable loss because that final determination lies solely with the U.S. department of agriculture
6 wildlife services and may not be changed by the board.
7 (c) The board shall hold a hearing on an appeal within 90 days of receipt of the written appeal,
8 allowing the staff adjuster and the producer to present their positions. A decision must be rendered by the
9 board within 30 days after the hearing. The producer must be notified in writing of the board's decision.
10 (7) As used in this section, the following definitions apply:
11 (a) "Confirmed" means reasonable physical evidence that livestock was actually attacked or killed
12 by a wolf, mountain lion, black bear, or grizzly bear, including but not limited to the presence of bite marks
13 indicative of the spacing of tooth punctures of wolves, mountain lions, black bear, or grizzly bears and
14 associated subcutaneous hemorrhaging and tissue damage indicating that the attack occurred while the animal
15 was alive, feeding patterns on the carcass, fresh tracks, scat, hair rubbed off on fences or brush, eyewitness
16 accounts, or other physical evidence that allows a reasonable inference of wolf, mountain lion, black bear, or
17 grizzly bear predation on an animal that has been largely consumed.
18 (b) "Fair market value" means:
19 (i) for commercial sheep more than 1 year old, the average price of sheep of similar age and sex
20 paid at the most recent Billings livestock sale ring or other ring as determined by the board;
21 (ii) for commercial lambs, the average market weaning value;
22 (iii) for registered sheep, twice the average value of commercial sheep of the same age and sex;
23 (iv) for commercial cattle more than 1 year old, the average price of cattle of similar age and sex
24 paid at the most recent Billings livestock sale ring or other ring as determined by the board;
25 (v) for commercial calves, the average market weaning value;
26 (vi) for registered cattle, twice the average value of commercial cattle of the same age and sex;
27 (vii) for other registered livestock, twice the average value of commercial-grade animals of the
28 same breed, age, and sex; or
